**As of today there have been no confirmed cases associated with any of the school districts in Fremont County.
September 11, 2020 @ 17:00
New Cases within Community: 1
New Cases within DOC and BOP offenders: None
Our current totals are: 166 total cases (149 positive cases, 17 probable cases), 1,456 negative tests, and 9 pending labs. There has been 1 death due to COVID-19.
This data comes from those tested at FCDPHE, St. Thomas More Hospital, and several medical provider offices within the county. These locations have tested 1,633 individuals. If a Fremont County resident is tested outside of the county and receives a positive result, then it will be included in this total. Thank you to all who are helping slow the spread of COVID-19 by wearing face masks (over your mouth and nose) in public, maintaining a physical distance of 6 ft when possible, and practicing frequent hand washing.
#FremontSeparatelyTogether

post_text:
International Overdose Awareness Day is a global event held on 31 August each year and aims to raise awareness of overdose and reduce the stigma of a drug-related death. It also acknowledges the grief felt by families and friends remembering those who have died or had a permanent injury as a result of drug overdose.

Learn more and get involved at: https://www.overdoseday.com/

post_text:
❓ Did you know? ❓

During this difficult time, the NAMI HelpLine is here for you. HelpLine volunteers are working to answer questions, offer support and provide practical next steps.

The relapse and overdose rate has increased by 30% since March 2020.

Mental health issues related to the pandemic can be especially hard for people with depression.

The NAMI HelpLine can be reached Monday through Friday, 10 am–6 pm, ET. Call 1-800-950-NAMI (6264) or e-mail info@nami.org. For more information about NAMI near Fremont County, visit NAMI Southeast Colorado.

post_text:
😷 How Does Your Breath Spread Virus Particles? 😷

Your breath is made up of oxygen, carbon dioxide, nitrogen and water vapor. Anytime a breath leaves your mouth, the gases in your breath cool and turn into liquid. Depending on the size, this liquid is also called water droplets or aerosol particles. Water droplets are larger. Gravity pulls them down to surfaces faster than they can evaporate. Smaller droplets and aerosol particles evaporate quickly, but they can travel with air currents for a period of time. A normal cough can spread particles more than 27 inches.

Source: https://aip.scitation.org/doi/10.1063/5.0015044

post_text:
The complaint form that is available through FCDPHE is the same complaint form that has been used to report environmental health concerns (unclean conditions at restaurants, tattoo parlors, child care facilities, etc.) and is an effective way to streamline feedback from the community that can be addressed and managed appropriately. In regards to state and local public health orders and mandates, this same form can be used to report business establishments and events that are not in compliance. This includes, but is not limited to, proper sanitization practices, the statewide mask mandate, or operating at an adjusted building capacity with appropriate space for social distancing. This does not include reporting individual citizens for not complying with state and local public health orders.

If you know of a business establishment or event that has done a great job promoting the health and safety of our community, please send a message including the name of the business and what they are doing well to fcdphe@fremontco.com or message us on Facebook so we can recognize their efforts.

It's okay to ask for help. 💛

Crisis Counseling Program (CCP) teams are not traditional mental health providers. Crisis counselors do not diagnose people or treat mental illness. Instead, crisis counselors are a combination of mental health paraprofessionals and professionals who support community members’ functioning and coping with disaster disruptions through crisis counseling services.

For more information, check out:
https://covid19.colorado.gov/get-help/coping-with-covid-19/crisis-counseling-program

According to the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment, this is considered a confirmed COVID-19 outbreak as it meets the criteria of “two or more confirmed cases of COVID-19 in a facility or (non-household) group with onset in a 14 day period.” FCDPHE is conducting case investigations to identify and notify people who may have been exposed to confirmed cases of COVID-19, but all members of the public are encouraged to do their part to slow the spread of COVID-19 in Fremont County by wearing a mask in public spaces, practicing social distancing, and washing their hands often.

Please view the press release for more information.

Congrats to the class of 2020! There are lots of great ways to celebrate the graduate in your life in a way that also celebrates public health and safety:
- Send a card
- Give them a call
- Send them a gift

Remember that COVID-19 cases are still rising in Fremont County, especially in the Canon City area. If you must be around non-household family and friends this weekend, remember to wash your hands thoroughly with soap and water for 20 seconds as soon as you enter someone else's home (and frequently depending on what surfaces you may be touching). Wear your mask (over your mouth and nose!) when inside buildings and even when in close contact with others outside. Maintain 6 ft. of physical distance when in a group setting. Thank you to all who have been doing their part to slow the spread of the virus that causes COVID-19 in Fremont County! Let's help our grads and their families stay healthy for bright futures!

post_text:
A possible public exposure notice is issued when there is a COVID-19 outbreak among individuals at a particular location. An outbreak, as defined by the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment, is two or more confirmed cases of COVID-19 in a facility or (non-household) group with onset in a 14 day period. An outbreak is considered over or "resolved" when 28 days have passed with no new illness.

What's the timeline?
A possible public exposure's timeline is determined by two days prior to the first symptomatic individual's symptom onset (or in the case of an asymptomatic individual, two days prior to receiving a positive test result) and the final day that a symptomatic individual was present at the location of the outbreak.

For more FAQ on outbreaks in Colorado, please visit: https://covid19.colorado.gov/data/outbreak-data. The data are updated weekly and may not yet include data from this week.

Using the infectious disease expertise of their existing research networks and global partners, NIAID has directed the networks to address the pressing need for vaccines and monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) against SARS-CoV-2. For more information, please visit: https://coronaviruspreventionnetwork.org/clinical-studies-faq/

post_text: You may know by now that Fremont County has entered a "mitigation period" as of 7/22/2020. Review the following graphics to learn more about what that means, how we got here, and what you (yes, you!) can do to help slow the spread of the virus that causes COVID-19 in Fremont County and help us keep our variance!
text: You may know by now that Fremont County has entered a "mitigation period" as of 7/22/2020. Review the following graphics to learn more about what that means, how we got here, and what you (yes, you!) can do to help slow the spread of the virus that causes COVID-19 in Fremont County and help us keep our variance!

post_text:
We'll *mitigate* this together!

As of 7/22/2020, Fremont County has entered a two week period of "mitigation".

So, what does that mean?
✅ Our most recent variance is still good
✅ Our community needs to support each other in slowing the spread of COVID-19, thus keeping our rate of infection low (and keeping things open!)
✅ If this does not happen and our rate of infection continues to increase, then we will be at risk of losing our variance

The graphic below indicates the process through which counties in Colorado must mitigate the spread of the virus that causes COVID-19 within their communities in order to keep their citizens safe and healthy, and maintain their variance requirements.

For more details regarding the thresholds of each rate of infection status (low, medium, and high), please visit: https://covid19.colorado.gov/safer-at-home-in-the-vast-great-outdoors/guidance-for-everyone/local-orders-variances

shared_text:
Ashley Smith, Cañon City Mayor
July 23 at 8:23 AM ·

COVID-19 UPDATE FROM Fremont County Department of Public Health & Environment - Colorado

Fremont County has exceeded the variance threshold and has now entered into the mitigation phase effective 7/22/2020. We have submitted our mitigation plan, and have two weeks from 7/22/2020 to monitor and mitigate the number of COVID-19 cases.

Our mitigation plan has a heavy emphasis on promoting mask-wearing, monitoring PPE and hospital capacity, and hiring a new staff member to help with COVID-19 duties.

Please help us stay open and promote social (physical) distancing, masks, and hand washing. We cannot do this without you!

🧐 Thinking About Quitting Smoking Or Vaping?
❓ Do You Have Questions?

The Colorado QuitLine can help. 🎉

The program is available to anyone over the age of 12. It’s completely free and you can enroll online in five minutes. There’s a text message program to help you deal with cravings. There’s a chat function that lets you talk to a coach online if you don’t want to talk over the phone. Coaches don’t need to speak to your parents, and all conversations are completely confidential. And even if you aren’t ready to quit, coaches at the QuitLine can help. For tips, tools, and support visit: https://coyouthquitline.org/

post_text:
Affected Area: Eastern Fremont County. Areas impacted include, but are not limited to Canon City, Lincoln Park, and Brookside

Advisory in Effect: 7:30 PM MDT, Wednesday, July 8, 2020 to 9:00 AM MDT, Thursday, July 9, 2020.

Public Health Recommendations: If smoke is thick or becomes thick in your neighborhood you may want to remain indoors. This is especially true for those with heart disease, respiratory illnesses, the very young, and the elderly. Consider limiting outdoor activity when moderate to heavy smoke is present. Consider relocating temporarily if smoke is present indoors and is making you ill. If visibility is less than 5 miles in smoke in your neighborhood, smoke has reached levels that are unhealthy.
Outlook: As the wind decreases Wednesday evening, smoke from the YMCA wildfire will begin to drain into lower lying areas surrounding the fire, including the Arkansas River and Grape Creek. Periods of moderate to heavy smoke will be possible in Canon City, Lincoln Park, and Brookside overnight Wednesday night and through early Thursday morning.

post_text:
Planning a trip for 4th of July weekend? 🇺🇸

Please consider these questions before making plans:
✅ Is COVID-19 spreading where you're going?
✅ Is COVID-19 spreading in your community?
✅ Will you or those you are traveling with be within 6 ft. of others during or after your trip?
✅ Are you or those you are traveling with more likely to get very ill from COVID-19?
✅ Do you live with someone who is more likely to get very ill from COVID-19?
✅ Does the state or local government where you live or at your destination require you to stay home for 14 days after traveling?
✅ If you get sick with COVID-19, will you have to miss work or school?

Please do not travel if you are sick, or if you have been around someone with COVID-19 in the past 14 days. Do not travel with someone who is sick. For more information on travel guidance, please visit: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-in-the-us.html

post_text: By learning more about how droplets travel (through talking, singing, coughing, and sneezing) we learn more about how we can slow the spread of the virus that causes COVID-19. Stay healthy and stay informed! 🤓
shared_text:
KHQ Kevin Kim
June 26 at 7:50 PM ·

Mask on? Mask off? Watch, then decide for yourself.

Huge shout out to Providence Sacred Heart and Holy Family/Providence Health Care, Eastern Washington for working with us on this story!

🎥: Aaron Calendine

Full disclaimer: this is a demonstration about droplets, not about how a virus (i.e. COVID-19) behaves or transmits. As Dr. Rich David said, "We used bacteria to show where the droplets go... The bacteria show where your secretions came from... These spots on the plates we're seeing, those are colonies of thousands of millions of bacteria that have just divided enough and multipled enough that we can actually visually see them on the plate."

tl;dr - Droplets transmit COVID-19. This is a demonstration on droplets.

As with the previous variance requests and PH orders; this approval is contingent upon conditions remaining controlled with no significant rise in confirmed COVID-19 cases. As we work to reopen Fremont County, please know that the Fremont County Department of Health and Environment is still extremely active in testing, monitoring, and prevention of COVID-19. This variance approval is the direct result of the tireless commitment from the Fremont County Department of Health and Environment and our community working hard to stay safe. Let's all hope numbers stay low and we can keep progressing towards all restrictions being lifted.

When our community has the capacity to test for COVID-19, the whole community wins. 🏆

Testing leads to quick identification of cases, quick treatment for those people and immediate isolation to prevent spread. Testing also is important in the bigger public health picture on mitigation efforts, helping investigators characterize the prevalence, spread and contagiousness of the disease. For more information on why testing is important, please visit: https://www.heart.org/en/news/2020/04/02/covid-19-science-why-testing-is-so-important

If you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of COVID-19, please make an appointment to be tested by calling 719-276-7450.

There are a number of actions youth sports organizations can take to help lower the risk of COVID-19 exposure and reduce the spread during competition and practice.

⚽️ The number of people a child or coach interacts with
🏀 How close physical contact is while interacting
🏈 How much equipment is shared by multiple players
🎾 The duration of the interaction

The risk of COVID-19 spread can be different, depending on the type of activity and depending on what precautions are in place. For more information, please visit: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/youth-sports.html

post_text:
The FCDPHE Daily Update includes totals for positive, negative, and pending tests. Pending means that the person has been tested (i.e. a sample has been collected) but the results have not yet been returned from the lab. While collecting the sample takes less than a minute, lab results sometimes take several days to be reported back to the agency that tested them.

Luckily, FCDPHE has staff on call to ensure each person who was tested at our facility can be notified as soon as their results have been reported--including evenings and weekends!

post_text:
What is HIPAA and why does patient privacy matter?

HIPAA stands for the "Healthcare Insurance Portability and Accountability Act". This law gives everyone rights over their own health information and sets rules and limits on who can look at and receive their health information. As a "covered entity" under HIPAA restrictions, FCDPHE can only disclose a portion of information regarding positive cases of COVID-19 including age and gender. This is especially important in smaller communities as even minimal knowledge and information can unintentionally reveal one's identity and therefore violate their patient privacy.

For more information, please visit: https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-individuals/guidance-materials-for-consumers/index.html

Collecting COVID-19: The Royal Gorge Regional Museum & History Center is looking to collect the local history of the pandemic to add to their public research files.

In 750 words or less, they are asking the public to share recollections of this historic period for future generations. Check out some example questions below to help get you started and visit https://museum.canoncity.org/ to participate.

• What was it like for you under the “Stay At Home” order?
• How did these events impact your personal and work life?
• How did your social interactions change?
• How has wearing a mask affected you?
• Did you adopt a new pet?
• Did you start a new hobby?

World's cutest public health advocate, Mick, is here to offer some helpful hints on how your mask should fit! 🐶

Here are a few more tips on face coverings from the CDC:
1. Wash your hands before putting on your face covering
2. Put it over your nose and mouth and secure it under your chin
3. Try to fit it snugly against the sides of your face
4. Make sure you can breathe easily

Starpoint
June 3 at 5:32 PM ·

Hi All! It's me, Mick, checking in for "WHAT'S UP WEDNESDAY!"

Today, I've been working on a public service announcement about the most effective way to wear your mask. Not to worry, I received several treats and belly rubs throughout. <3

I would love to know what you have been up to. You can post a photo in the comments below.

#whosagoodboy

*Upon further investigation it was determined that the positive case reported on 5/24 did not meet case definition for ‘confirmed’ or ‘probable’ and so has been removed from our case count.

**Probable cases are defined as "cases where public health epidemiologists have determined that infection is highly likely because a person exhibited symptoms and had close contact with someone who tested positive”.

This data comes from those tested at FCDPHE, St. Thomas More Hospital, and several medical provider offices within the county. Please note numbers may not add up due to Fremont County residents being tested outside of the county. Thank you to all who are helping slow the spread of COVID-19. Stay safer at home and stay healthy.

El Paso County Public Health
May 18 at 3:00 PM ·

No matter how small your group may be, it’s important to take the following actions when gathering with people outside your household:

• Consider meeting virtually. If that’s not possible, make sure you apply the rest of this guidance.
• Keep your group to 10 or less.
• Maintain 6 feet of distance between yourself and those who are not part of your household.
• Ask that anyone who is feeling sick stay home.
• Ask that everyone use cloth face coverings to protect the group in case someone is contagious and not experiencing symptoms.

Learn more here: https://www.elpasocountyhealth.org/protecting-our-community
text:

May 18 at 3:00 PM ·

No matter how small your group may be, it’s important to take the following actions when gathering with people outside your household:

• Consider meeting virtually. If that’s not possible, make sure you apply the rest of this guidance.
• Keep your group to 10 or less.
• Maintain 6 feet of distance between yourself and those who are not part of your household.
• Ask that anyone who is feeling sick stay home.
• Ask that everyone use cloth face coverings to protect the group in case someone is contagious and not experiencing symptoms.

As of May 17th there are no new cases. This means our current totals are: 25 total cases (20 positive cases, 5 probable cases*), 375 negative tests, and 1 pending lab. In Fremont County, 403 have been tested and of the positive and probable cases 21 have recovered.

*Probable cases are defined as "cases where public health epidemiologists have determined that infection is highly likely because a person exhibited symptoms and had close contact with someone who tested positive”.

Individuals who receive an inconclusive test result are promptly retested and their final result is included in the total count. FCDPHE now has increased testing capacity and will only report the final test result so as to only count individuals once.

Please note numbers may not add up due to Fremont County residents being tested outside of the county. Thank you to all who are helping slow the spread of COVID-19. Stay safer at home and stay healthy.

post_text:
What makes a COVID-19 test "inconclusive"?

In order to identify the SARS-CoV-2 virus that causes COVID-19, researchers use a method called reverse transcription PCR (RT-PCR) to look for two specific genes.

The test is:
POSITIVE: If both genes are found
NEGATIVE: If neither genes are found
INCONCLUSIVE: If only one gene is found

Individuals tested at FCDPHE who receive an inconclusive test result are promptly retested and their final result is included in the total count provided by the daily update. FCDPHE now has increased testing capacity and will only report the final test result so as to only count individuals once.

For more information, please visit: https://www.healthline.com/health/coronavirus-diagnosis
